  "response": "# Diagnosing CI-only Timeouts: A Deterministic Diff-First Approach\n\nCI-only timeouts are particularly challenging because they don't reproduce locally. Here's a systematic approach to diagnose the issue:\n\n## 1. Identify When the Problem Started\n\n- Find the first failing build by bisecting the CI history\n- Compare with the last successful build to identify the specific commit that introduced the timeout\n\n## 2. Analyze the Changes (Diff-First)\n\n- Examine the diff between the last successful and first failing builds\n- Look specifically for:\n  - Changes to timeouts or timing-related configurations\n  - New dependencies or version upgrades\n  - Changes to async operations or concurrency patterns\n  - Resource usage increases (memory, CPU, network calls)\n  - New or modified tests that might be flaky\n\n## 3. Analyze CI Environment vs Local\n\n- Compare resource constraints (CPU, memory, disk I/O)\n- Check for network differences (latency, bandwidth, firewall rules)\n- Verify dependency versions match exactly\n- Check for environment variables that differ\n\n## 4. Instrument the CI Build\n\n- Add detailed timing logs at key points in the service\n- Capture resource metrics (CPU, memory, I/O) during execution\n- Add debug logs around suspicious operations identified in the diff\n- Implement progressive timeouts to narrow down where the hang occurs\n\n## 5. Reproduce with Constraints\n\n- Simulate CI constraints locally (CPU/memory limits, network throttling)\n- Use containerization to match CI environment more closely\n- Try running tests in sequence rather than parallel to isolate issues\n\n## 6. Targeted Experiments\n\n- Create a minimal reproduction by selectively applying parts of the diff\n- Temporarily revert suspicious changes to confirm the culprit\n- Add instrumentation specifically around timeout-prone operations\n\n## 7. Common Timeout Causes to Check\n\n- Race conditions exposed by CI's constrained resources\n- Network calls without 